LAMMPS
```json
{
  "application": "LAMMPS",
  "software": [
    "mpirun",
    "lmp_intel_cpu"
  ],
  "resources": {
    "nodes": 1,
    "time": "12:00:00",
    "input_file": "in.lj",
    "precision": ["single", "mixed", "double"],
    "dimensions": {
      "x": 32,
      "y": 32,
      "z": 32,
      "t": 100
    },
    "processors": [1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 16]
  },
  "output_files": [
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.1",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.2",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.4",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.6",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.8",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.10",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.12",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.14",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.single.128K.16",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.1",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.2",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.4",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.6",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.8",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.10",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.12",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.14",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.mixed.128K.16",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.1",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.2",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.4",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.6",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.8",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.10",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.12",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.14",
    "log.10Sep14.lj.intel.cpu.double.128K.16"
  ]
}
```
This script runs LAMMPS (Large-scale Atomic/Molecular Massively Parallel Simulator). It uses the Intel-optimized version of LAMMPS (`lmp_intel_cpu`), and it uses `mpirun` to run the simulation on a cluster.

The script sets up a series of simulations with different numbers of processors (from 1 to 16), using the Intel MPI implementation (`-sf intel -pk intel`). It runs the simulations with three different precision levels: `single`, `mixed`, and `double`. The simulations are run with a system size of 32x32x32, and they run for 100 timesteps.

The script also renames the log files from `log.lammps` to something more descriptive, including the date, the type of LAMMPS executable, the precision level, the number of processors, and the system size.
